00:01:03.120 --> 00:01:06.859
discussion of women getting the right to vote
with the passage of the 19th amendment, but

00:01:06.859 --> 00:01:10.270
if we focus too much on the constitutional
history, we’re gonna miss a lot.

00:01:10.270 --> 00:01:14.659
Some historians refer to the thirty years
between 1890 and 1920 as the “women’s

00:01:14.659 --> 00:01:18.450
era” because it was in that time that women
started to have greater economic and political

00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:19.450
opportunities.

00:01:19.450 --> 00:01:23.360
Women were also aided by legal changes, like
getting the right to own property, control

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:25.799
their wages and make contracts and wills.

00:01:25.799 --> 00:01:30.799
By 1900 almost 5 million women worked for
wages, mainly in domestic service or light

00:01:30.799 --> 00:01:32.850
manufacturing, like the garment industry.

00:01:32.850 --> 00:01:36.829
Women in America were always vital contributors
to the economy as producers and consumers

00:01:36.829 --> 00:01:41.219
and they always worked, whether for wages
or taking care of children and the home.

00:01:41.219 --> 00:01:44.909
And as someone who has recently returned from
paternity leave, let me tell you, that ain’t

00:01:44.909 --> 00:01:45.909
no joke.

00:01:45.909 --> 00:01:50.179
And American women were also active as reformers
since, like, America became a thing.

00:01:50.179 --> 00:01:54.020
And those reform movements brought women into
state and national politics before the dawn

00:01:54.020 --> 00:01:55.189
of the progressive era.

00:01:55.189 --> 00:01:59.439
Unfortunately, their greatest achievement,
Prohibition, was also our greatest national

00:01:59.439 --> 00:02:00.439
shame.

00:02:00.439 --> 00:02:01.439
Oh, yeah, alright, okay.

00:02:01.439 --> 00:02:05.130
It’s actually not in our top 5 national
shames.

00:02:05.130 --> 00:02:08.860
But, probably women’s greatest influence
indeed came through membership AND leadership

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:11.350
in the Women’s Christian Temperance Union.

00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:18.440
The WCTU was founded in 1874 and by 1890 it
had 150,000 members, making it the largest

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:20.450
female organization in the United States.

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:24.830
Under the leadership of Frances Willard, the
WCTU embraced a broad reform agenda.

00:02:24.830 --> 00:02:27.390
Like it included pushing for the right for
women to vote.

00:02:27.390 --> 00:02:31.040
The feeling was that the best way to stop
people from drinking was to pass local laws

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:35.510
that made it harder to drink, and to do that
it would be very helpful if women could vote.

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:38.940
Because American men were a bunch of alcoholic
scoundrels who darn well weren’t going to

00:02:38.940 --> 00:02:40.970
vote to get rid of beer hoses.

00:02:40.970 --> 00:02:46.170
In 1895 Willard boldly declared, “A wider
freedom is coming to the women of America.

00:02:46.170 --> 00:02:50.930
Too long has it been held that woman has no
right to enter these movements (…) Politics

00:02:50.930 --> 00:02:52.340
is the place for woman.”

00:02:52.340 --> 00:02:55.870
But the role of women in politics did greatly
expand during the Progressive era.

00:02:55.870 --> 00:03:00.220
As in prior decades, many reformers were middle
and upper class women, but the growing economy

00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:04.190
and the expansion of what might be called
the upper-middle class meant that there were

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:09.390
more educational opportunities and this growing
group of college-educated women leaned in

00:03:09.390 --> 00:03:11.510
and became the leaders of new movements.

00:03:11.510 --> 00:03:13.680
