00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:18.420
So as we’ve talked about before, the 1890s
saw the dawning of the American mass consumer

00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:22.490
society and many of the new products made
in the second wave of industrialization were

00:03:22.490 --> 00:03:26.420
aimed at women, especially “labor-saving”
devices like washing machines.

00:03:26.420 --> 00:03:30.780
If you’ve ever had an infant, you might
notice that they poop and barf on everything

00:03:30.780 --> 00:03:31.780
all the time.

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:35.470
Like, I recently called the pediatrician and
I was like, “My 14-day-old daughter poops

00:03:35.470 --> 00:03:36.751
fifteen times a day.”

00:03:36.751 --> 00:03:38.990
And he was like, “If anything, that seems
low.”

00:03:38.990 --> 00:03:41.260
So the washing machine is a real game-changer.

00:03:41.260 --> 00:03:46.000
And many women realized that being the primary
consumers who did the shopping for the home

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.210
gave them powerful leverage to bring about
change.

00:03:49.210 --> 00:03:53.690
Chief among these was Florence Kelley, a college-educated
woman who after participating in a number

00:03:53.690 --> 00:03:57.810
of progressive reform causes came to head
the National Consumers League.

00:03:57.810 --> 00:04:02.440
The League sponsored boycotts and shaped consumption
patterns encouraging consumers to buy products

00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:06.030
that were made without child or what we now
would call sweatshop labor.

00:04:06.030 --> 00:04:08.490
Which at the time was often just known as
“labor.”

00:04:08.490 --> 00:04:12.260
And there was also a subtle shift in gender
roles as more and more women worked outside

00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:13.260
the home.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:17.499
African American women continued to work primarily
as domestic servants or in agriculture, and

00:04:17.499 --> 00:04:22.079
immigrant women mostly did low-paying factory
labor, but for native-born white women there

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:25.060
were new opportunities, especially in office
work.

00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:28.020
And this points to how technology created
opportunities for women.

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:31.039
Like, almost all the telephone operators in
the U.S. were women.

00:04:31.039 --> 00:04:36.879
By 1920 office workers and telephone operators
made up 25% of the female workforce, while

00:04:36.879 --> 00:04:38.999
domestic servants were only 15%.

00:04:38.999 --> 00:04:43.240
A union leader named Abraham Bisno remarked
that working gave immigrant women a sense

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:47.590
of independence: “They acquired the right
to personality, something alien to the highly

00:04:47.590 --> 00:04:50.340
patriarchal family structures of the old country.”

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:53.730
Of course this also meant that young women
were often in conflict with their parents,

00:04:53.730 --> 00:04:58.699
as a job brought more freedom, money, and
perhaps, if they were lucky, a room of one’s

00:04:58.699 --> 00:04:59.699
own.

