00:05:55.509 --> 00:05:56.509
What?

00:05:56.509 --> 00:05:57.509
Aaaaaah!

00:05:57.509 --> 00:06:00.979
The idea that having a job is valuable just
for the independence that it brings and as

00:06:00.979 --> 00:06:05.629
a form of “individual expression” was
pretty radical, as most women, and especially

00:06:05.629 --> 00:06:09.860
most men, were not comfortable with the idea
that being a housewife was similar to being

00:06:09.860 --> 00:06:12.039
a servant to one’s husband and children.

00:06:12.039 --> 00:06:15.889
But of course that changes when staying at
home becomes one of many choices rather than

00:06:15.889 --> 00:06:17.449
your only available option.

00:06:17.449 --> 00:06:19.949
And then came birth control.

00:06:19.949 --> 00:06:21.159
Huzzah!

00:06:21.159 --> 00:06:24.330
Women who needed to work wanted a way to limit
the number of pregnancies.

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:28.389
Being pregnant and having a baby can make
it difficult to hold down a job and also babies

00:06:28.389 --> 00:06:31.159
are diaper-using, stuff-breaking, consumptive
machines.

00:06:31.159 --> 00:06:32.460
They basically eat money.

00:06:32.460 --> 00:06:33.460
And we love them.

00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:37.080
But birth control advocates like Margaret
Sanger and Emma Goldman also argued that women

00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:40.599
should be able to enjoy sex without having
children.

00:06:40.599 --> 00:06:42.599
To which men said, “Women can enjoy sex?”

00:06:42.599 --> 00:06:47.490
Believe it or not, that was seen as a pretty
radical idea and it lead to changes in sexual

00:06:47.490 --> 00:06:50.490
behavior including more overall skoodilypooping.

00:06:50.490 --> 00:06:54.729
Goldman was arrested more than 40 times for
sharing these dangerous ideas about female

00:06:54.729 --> 00:06:57.490
sexuality and birth control and she was eventually
deported.

00:06:57.490 --> 00:07:01.339
Sanger, who worked to educate working class
women about birth control, was sentenced to

00:07:01.339 --> 00:07:06.360
prison in 1916 for opening a clinic in Brooklyn
that distributed contraceptive devices to

00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:07.400
poor immigrant women.

00:07:07.400 --> 00:07:10.499
The fight over birth control is important
for at least three reasons.

00:07:10.499 --> 00:07:14.370
First, it put women into the forefront of
debates about free speech in America.

00:07:14.370 --> 00:07:17.960
I mean, some of the most ardent advocates
of birth control were also associated with

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:20.500
the IWW and the Socialist Party.

00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:24.931
Secondly, birth control is also a public health
issue and many women during the progressive

00:07:24.931 --> 00:07:29.440
era entered public life to bring about changes
related to public health, leading the crusade

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:33.089
against tuberculosis, the so-called White
Plague, and other diseases.

00:07:33.089 --> 00:07:35.520
Thirdly, it cut across class lines.

00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:39.479
Having or not having children is an issue
for all women, regardless of whether they

00:07:39.479 --> 00:07:44.050
went to college, and the birth control movement
brought upper, middle, and lower class women

00:07:44.050 --> 00:07:47.080
together in ways that other social movements
never did.

00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:50.369
Another group of Progressive women took up
the role of addressing the problems of the

00:07:50.369 --> 00:07:52.949
poor and spearheaded the Settlement House
movement.

00:07:52.949 --> 00:07:55.150
The key figure here was Jane Addams.

00:07:55.150 --> 00:07:57.310
My God, there are still Adamses in American
history?

00:07:57.310 --> 00:08:00.789
Oh, she spells it Addams-family-Addams, not
like founding-fathers-Adams.

00:08:00.789 --> 00:08:04.020
Anyway, she started Hull House in Chicago
in 1889.

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:08.130
Settlement houses became the incubators of
the new field of social work, a field in which

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:09.520
women played a huge part.

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:13.509
And Addams became one of America’s most
important spokespeople for progressive ideas.

00:08:13.509 --> 00:08:17.979
And yet in many places, while all of this
was happening, women could not technically

00:08:17.979 --> 00:08:18.979
vote.

00:08:18.979 --> 00:08:21.229
But their increasing involvement in social
movements at the turn of the 20th century

00:08:21.229 --> 00:08:23.560
led them to electoral politics.

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:27.860
It’s true that women were voting before
the passage of the 19th amendment in 1920.

00:08:27.860 --> 00:08:32.070
Voting is a state issue, and in many western
states, women were granted the right to vote

00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:33.610
in the late 19th century.

00:08:33.610 --> 00:08:37.240
States could also grant women the right to
run for office, which explains how the first

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:41.110
Congresswoman, Jeannette Rankin, could vote
against America’s entry into World War I

00:08:41.110 --> 00:08:42.120
in 1917.

00:08:42.120 --> 00:08:47.050
That said, the passage and ratification of
the 19th Amendment is a big deal in American

00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:48.050
history.

00:08:48.050 --> 00:08:49.139
It’s also a recent deal.

00:08:49.139 --> 00:08:54.279
Like, when my grandmothers were born, women
could not vote in much of the United States.

00:08:54.279 --> 00:08:58.860
The amendment says that states cannot deny
people the right to vote because they are

00:08:58.860 --> 00:09:02.190
women, which isn’t as interesting as the
political organization and activity that led

00:09:02.190 --> 00:09:03.190
to its passage.

00:09:03.190 --> 00:09:04.310
Alright, let’s go to the Thought Bubble.

00:09:04.310 --> 00:09:07.000
The suffrage movement was extremely fragmented.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:11.690
There was a first wave of suffrage, exemplified
by the women at Seneca Falls, and this metamorphosed

00:09:11.690 --> 00:09:16.290
into the National American Women’s Suffrage
Association, or NAWSA.

00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:20.440
Most of the leadership of NAWSA was made up
of middle to upper class women, often involved

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:25.330
in other progressive causes, who unfortunately
sometimes represented the darker side of the

00:09:25.330 --> 00:09:26.330
suffrage movement.

00:09:26.330 --> 00:09:30.430
Because these upper class progressives frequently
used nativist arguments to make their claims

00:09:30.430 --> 00:09:31.740
for the right to vote.

00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:35.810
They argued that if the vote could be granted
to ignorant immigrants, some of whom could

00:09:35.810 --> 00:09:39.290
barely speak English, then it should also
be granted to native born women.

00:09:39.290 --> 00:09:43.930
This isn’t to say that the elitist arguments
won the day, but they should be acknowledged.

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:48.000
By the early 20th century a new generation
of college-educated activists had arrived

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:49.000
on the scene.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:52.180
And many of these women were more radical
than early suffrage supporters.

00:09:52.180 --> 00:09:56.250
They organized the National Women’s Party
and, under the leadership of Alice Paul, pushed

00:09:56.250 --> 00:09:59.940
for the vote using aggressive tactics that
many of the early generation of women’s

00:09:59.940 --> 00:10:01.370
rights advocates found unseemly.

00:10:01.370 --> 00:10:06.720
Paul had been studying in Britain between
1907 and 1910 where she saw the more militant

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:08.380
women’s rights activists at work.

00:10:08.380 --> 00:10:13.430
She adopted their tactics that included protests
leading to imprisonment and loud denunciations

00:10:13.430 --> 00:10:15.959
of the patriarchy that would make tumblr proud.

00:10:15.959 --> 00:10:20.540
And during World War I she compared Wilson
to the Kaiser and Paul and her followers chained

00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:22.250
themselves to the White House fence.

00:10:22.250 --> 00:10:25.709
The activists then started a hunger strike
during their 7-month prison sentence and had

00:10:25.709 --> 00:10:27.410
to be force-fed.

00:10:27.410 --> 00:10:32.120
Woodrow Wilson had half-heartedly endorsed
women’s suffrage in 1916, but the war split

00:10:32.120 --> 00:10:33.410
the movement further.

00:10:33.410 --> 00:10:37.209
Most suffrage organizations believed that
wartime service would help women earn respect

00:10:37.209 --> 00:10:38.209
and equal rights.

00:10:38.209 --> 00:10:42.319
But other activists, like many Progressives,
opposed the war and regarded it as a potential

00:10:42.319 --> 00:10:43.589
threat to social reform.

00:10:43.589 --> 00:10:46.490
But, in the end, the war did sort of end up
helping the cause.

00:10:46.490 --> 00:10:51.100
Patriotic support of the war by women, especially
their service working in wartime industries,

00:10:51.100 --> 00:10:54.310
convinced many that it was just wrong to deny
them the right to vote.

00:10:54.310 --> 00:10:58.610
And the mistreatment of Alice Paul and other
women in prison for their cause created outrage

00:10:58.610 --> 00:11:02.250
that further pushed the Wilson administration
to support enfranchising women.

00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:03.250
Thanks, Thought Bubble.

00:11:03.250 --> 00:11:06.750
So, women’s long fight to gain the right
to vote ended with the ratification of the

00:11:06.750 --> 00:11:08.200
19th Amendment in 1920.

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:12.350
But, in some ways, the final granting of the
franchise was a bit anti-climactic.

00:11:12.350 --> 00:11:16.750
For one thing, it was overshadowed by the
18th Amendment, Prohibition, which affected

00:11:16.750 --> 00:11:18.970
both women and men in large numbers.

00:11:18.970 --> 00:11:19.970
Also Gatsbys.

00:11:19.970 --> 00:11:23.819
You could say a lot of bad things about Prohibition,
and I have, but the crusade against alcohol

00:11:23.819 --> 00:11:29.160
did galvanize and politicize many women, and
organizations such as the WCTU and the Anti-Saloon

00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:31.660
League introduced yet more to political activism.

00:11:31.660 --> 00:11:35.890
But, while the passage of the 19th amendment
was a huge victory, Alice Paul and the National

00:11:35.890 --> 00:11:39.970
Women’s Party were unable to muster the
same support for an Equal Rights Amendment.

00:11:39.970 --> 00:11:45.140
Paul believed that women needed equal access
to education and employment opportunities.

00:11:45.140 --> 00:11:48.779
And here they came into contact with other
women’s groups, especially the League of

00:11:48.779 --> 00:11:53.560
Women Voters and the Women’s Trade Union
League, which opposed the ERA fearing that

00:11:53.560 --> 00:11:58.139
equal rights would mean an unraveling of hard-won
benefits like mother’s pensions and laws

00:11:58.139 --> 00:11:59.720
limiting women’s hours of labor.

00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:03.699
So, the ERA failed, and then another proposed
amendment that would have given Congress the

00:12:03.699 --> 00:12:10.420
power to limit child labor won ratification
in only 6 states.

00:12:10.420 --> 00:12:18.441
So in many ways the period between 1890 and
1920, which roughly corresponds to the Progressive

00:12:18.441 --> 00:12:21.709
Era, was the high tide of women’s rights
and political activism.

00:12:21.709 --> 00:12:25.940
It culminated in the ratification of the 19th
amendment, but the right to vote didn’t

00:12:25.940 --> 00:12:30.310
lead to significant legislation that actually
improved the lives of women, at least not

00:12:30.310 --> 00:12:31.310
for a while.

00:12:31.310 --> 00:12:34.351
Nor were there immediate changes in the roles
that women were expected to play in the social

00:12:34.351 --> 00:12:35.930
order as wives and mothers.

00:12:35.930 --> 00:12:40.280
Still, women were able to increase their autonomy
and freedom in the burgeoning consumer marketplace.

00:12:40.280 --> 00:12:44.600
But it’s important to note that like other
oppressed populations in American history,

00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:48.920
women weren’t given these rights, they had
to fight for the rights that were said to

00:12:48.920 --> 00:12:49.920
